| `full_name` | TEXT | Displayed as "Insured by" on policy emails |

### `policies` table
| Column | Type | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| [id](file:///c:/Users/Haram/Desktop/rac%20clone/src/components/BenefitGrid.tsx#37-73) | INTEGER (PK, auto) | |
| `policy_number` | TEXT (unique) | Serialized: `RAC-000001`, `RAC-000002`, etc. |
| `first_name` | TEXT | |
| `last_name` | TEXT | |
| `dob` | TEXT | ISO date string |
| `license_number` | TEXT | |
| `occupation` | TEXT | |
| `address1` | TEXT | |
| `address2` | TEXT | nullable |
| `city` | TEXT | |
| `postcode` | TEXT | |
| `mobile` | TEXT | |
| `email` | TEXT | |
| `vehicle_reg` | TEXT | |
| `vehicle_make` | TEXT | |
| `vehicle_model` | TEXT | |
| `vehicle_year` | INTEGER | |
| `amount` | REAL | £ amount |
| `insurance_start` | TEXT | ISO datetime |
| `insurance_end` | TEXT | ISO datetime |
| `admin_id` | INTEGER (FK → admins.id) | Who created this policy |
| `use_alt_email` | INTEGER | 0 or 1 |
| `created_at` | TEXT | ISO datetime |

---

## Policy Number Generation

- Format: `RAC-XXXXXX` (e.g. `RAC-000001`, `RAC-000002`)
- On each new policy: query `MAX(id)` from policies table, add 1, zero-pad to 6 digits
- This keeps numbers serialized and ordered

---

## Email Template

```
Subject: Your RAC Insurance Policy Confirmation

Hi, [First Name] [Last Name]

Thank you for choosing RAC Short-Term Car Insurance.
Your policy has been created successfully. Here are your details:

═══════════════════════════════════════
  POLICY DETAILS
═══════════════════════════════════════

  Policy Number:    RAC-000042
  Policy Start:     15 Mar 2026, 09:00 AM
  Policy End:       17 Mar 2026, 09:00 AM
  Insured by:       Admin Name
  Duration:         2 days 0 hours
  Vehicle:          Tesla Model 3 (LX20 ABC)
  Amount:           £250.00

═══════════════════════════════════════

If you need to retrieve your policy info, visit:
https://[your-domain]/retrieve-info

For support, call 0330 159 1111.

RAC Motoring Services
```

---

## Duration Calculation

```
diff = end_date - start_date (in milliseconds)
days  = Math.floor(diff / 86400000)
hours = Math.floor((diff % 86400000) / 3600000)
→ "2 days 3 hours"
```

